{"type":"message","id":"0b576173","parentId":"3dde7927","timestamp":"2026-03-16T06:34:46.671Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"**Reflecting on self-improvement**\n\nI need to respond to criticism properly by acknowledging it and mentioning ways I can improve. The user suggests I should learn and improve, so logging these insights makes sense. I’ll note concrete changes, like not fixating on mistakes, searching with external resources sooner, and validating with devices. I could write this into memory since it's a durable improvement. It seems essential to keep a self-improvement log based on the user's feedback. Overall, I'll focus on documenting these lessons.**Considering memory and improvements**\n\nI’m pondering whether to store information in long-term memory. While my current workspace memory file is in use, I could log my learning instead. Editing the memory for the date could work, but it's fine to use memory_store too. Durable memories usually go in files, but it's not strict for every turn. The user has mentioned learning and improvement, so I should consider making concrete changes. Maybe I should update my rules regarding processes tied to mobile bugs and how to handle them effectively.**Updating AGENTS for improvement**\n\nI need to focus on the user's request about learning and improving, which points to a workflow enhancement for AGENTS. I could create a new rule addressing mobile and device compatibility bugs: after one failed attempt followed by a confirmatory retest, I should pivot to an alternative architecture. Validating any external artifacts before committing to a path is essential. It might be helpful to consider using the openclaw-workspace skill for these updates and adhere to instructions for skill application while maintaining the workspace file.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"你说得对。这次不是“慢一点”这么简单，而是**判断路径和推进方式都有问题**。我先把这次的教训落进规则，不停留在道歉上。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_vXxcK9JbBuLEH83ra2b9yPIt","name":"self_improvement_log","arguments":{"type":"learning","area":"backend","category":"best_practice","priority":"high","summary":"For mobile compatibility bugs, stop patching a broken vendor system path after one confirmatory retest; pivot earlier to an alternative owned path and verify required assets upfront","details":"On the Kids Box TV App read-along bug, I spent too long patching Xiaomi system SpeechRecognizer compatibility before decisively switching to the offline sherpa path. I also failed to verify model asset availability upfront, which delayed real progress. The eventual breakthrough came from obtaining and packaging the actual sherpa model assets, not from further system-ASR patching.","suggestedAction":"For future mobile runtime bugs: (1) verify external assets/dependencies exist before promising a path, (2) after one failed vendor-path patch and one confirmatory retest, pivot to the alternative path the app can own, (3) proactively report each new artifact/blocker without waiting for the user to ask."}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"gmn","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1773642853575}}
